snippet.textDisplay: Ugh I wish I would have personally known you so I could have helped you out! (I live in nyc too) and honestly the BEST advice I can give to anyone that is looking into moving to nyc is APPLY FOR LOTTERY APARTMENTS!! It’s basically an easier and better way to go apartment hunting AND they narrow down the apartments based on what you make already. Long story short they help you look for cheap apartments based on your income. I hope this comment gets seen and helps anyone who’s interested! Also side note, nyc is not THAT expensive, there are studio and even one bedroom apartments that go from $500-$1400 a month that still look this good so don’t be intimidated because $2000 is a LOT for a studio lol

snippet.textDisplay: THe no broker fee is horrible news.  First, realtors arent going to show apts for free, so the brokers fee is included in the rent and prices jumped immediately 7% after it passed.  Now, after your year, are the landlords going to drop the price of rent since the broker has been paid?  nope....so youre stuck subscribing to the broker.  Trust me, it was better to pay the broker fee.

snippet.textDisplay:
Advice from a New Yorker (I just bought my first apt here!)
1) Stop looking downtown. UWS, Morningside Heights, & Harlem are cheaper and you'll get a better apartment. And its still easy to get downtown when you want to.
2) Have first and last months rent for deposit
3) Don't stretch your budget at all. NYC is EXPENSIVE.
4) Always always always try to get a rent controlled apartment, even if it means getting a roommate.

snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone: apartment searching in NY is very hard. By standard you need at least a 1 months rent, security (another months rent), and possibly a brokers fee which is a large percentage to even have an application considered. Plus good credit and you, you family or roommates living with you, have to have a combined income 40 times the rent. There are exceptions to the rule but you would be lucky to find such a thing. Just throwing information out there for those looking to move to NY.

The info in the video is pretty correct!
